<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5> give someone the big eye • look at someone with big eyes</xh5><p> <i>give someone the big eye</i>—(coll.) look at a person with an open display of romantic interest <i>(also: give someone the eye):</i> I can feel my dander rise watching him <u>give her the big eye</u>. </p><p><i>look at someone with big eyes</i>—<i>(also: look at someone wideeyed)</i> stare at a person in surprise: “Are we having a son?” he asked, <u>looking at her with big eyes</u> shining from happiness.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> The expression does not correlate in meaning with the saying <b>one’s eyes are bigger than his stomach</b>—one wants more of smth. than he can handle: <u>His eyes are bigger than his stomach</u>, or converted to garden terms, he would like to grow more varieties than his land can accommodate.</p> </entry>
